1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:06,578
Book 9 Ulysses declares himself, and begins his story, The Psychons, Lotophagi, and Cyclopes.

2
00:00:07,178 --> 00:00:13,224
And Ulysses answered, King Alcinous, it is a good thing to hear a bard with such a divine voice as this man has.

3
00:00:13,244 --> 00:00:25,837
There is nothing better or more delightful than when a whole people make merry together, with the guests sitting orderly to listen, while the table is loaded with bread and meats, and the cup-bearer draws wine and fills his cup for every man.

4
00:00:26,358 --> 00:00:29,481
This is indeed as fair a sight as a man can see.

5
00:00:29,579 --> 00:00:43,191
Now, however, since you are inclined to ask the story of my sorrows and rekindle my own sad memories in respect of them, I do not know how to begin, nor yet how to continue and conclude my tale, for the hand of heaven has been laid heavily upon me.

6
00:00:43,793 --> 00:00:47,301
Firstly, then, I will tell you my name that you too may know it.

7
00:00:47,281 --> 00:00:53,549
And one day, if I outlive this time of sorrow, may become my guests, though I live so far away from all of you.

8
00:00:54,069 --> 00:01:00,517
I am Ulysses, son of Laertes, renowned among mankind for all manner of subtlety, so that my fame ascends to heaven.

9
00:01:01,078 --> 00:01:12,732
I live in Ithaca, where there is a high mountain called Neritum, covered with forests, and not far from it there is a group of islands very near to one another, Delicium, Same, and the wooded island of Zakynthos.

10
00:01:12,712 --> 00:01:20,562
It lies squat on the horizon, all highest up in the sea towards the sunset, while the others lie away from it towards dawn point seven five.

11
00:01:21,322 --> 00:01:27,090
It is a rugged island, but it breeds brave men, and my eyes know none that they better love to look upon.

12
00:01:27,130 --> 00:01:40,626
The goddess Calypso kept me with her in her cave, and wanted me to marry her, as did also the cunning Aean goddess Circe, but they could neither of them persuade me, for there is nothing dearer to a man than his own country and his parents,

13
00:01:40,606 --> 00:01:46,995
and however splendid a home he may have in a foreign country, if it be far from father or mother, he does not care about it.

14
00:01:47,696 --> 00:01:53,484
Now, however, I will tell you of the many hazardous adventures which, by Jove's will, I met with on my return from Troy.

15
00:01:54,225 --> 00:01:58,631
When I had set sail thence the wind took me first to Ismaris, which is the city of the Seacons.

16
00:01:59,212 --> 00:02:01,956
There I sacked the town and put the people to the sword.

17
00:02:01,936 --> 00:02:08,229
We took their wives and also much booty, which we divided equitably amongst us, so that none might have reason to complain.

18
00:02:08,249 --> 00:02:18,070
I then said that we had better make off at once, but my men very foolishly would not obey me, so they stayed there drinking much wine and killing great numbers of sheep and oxen on the seashore.

19
00:02:18,871 --> 00:02:23,100
Meanwhile the Seacons cried out for help to other Seacons who lived inland.

20
00:02:23,165 --> 00:02:32,053
These were more in number, and stronger, and they were more skilled in the art of war, for they could fight, either from chariots or on foot as the occasion served.

21
00:02:32,373 --> 00:02:39,359
In the morning, therefore, they came as thick as leaves and bloom in summer, and a hand of heaven was against us, so that we were hard-pressed.

22
00:02:39,759 --> 00:02:45,944
They set the battle in a ray near the ships, and the hosts aimed their bronze-shod spears at one another twaint seven six.

23
00:02:46,745 --> 00:02:52,530
So long as the day waxed and it was still morning, we held our own against them, though they were more in number than we.

24
00:02:52,510 --> 00:03:02,230
But as the sun went down, towards the time when men loosed their oxen, the Seacons got the better of us, and we lost half a dozen men from every ship we had, so we got away with those that were left.

25
00:03:02,771 --> 00:03:08,443
Thence we sailed onward with sorrow in our hearts, but glad to have escaped death, though we had lost our comrades.

26
00:03:08,491 --> 00:03:13,820
Nor did we leave till we had thrice invoked each one of the poor fellows who had perished by the hands of the Siccans.

27
00:03:14,681 --> 00:03:22,854
Then Jove raised the north wind against us till it blew a hurricane, so that land and sky were hidden in thick clouds, and night sprang forth out of the heavens.

28
00:03:23,435 --> 00:03:32,710
We let the ships run before the gale, but the force of the wind tore our sails to tatters, so we took them down for fear of shipwreck and rowed our hardest towards the land.

29
00:03:32,690 --> 00:03:37,645
There we lay two days and two nights, suffering much alike from toil and distress of mind.

30
00:03:38,126 --> 00:03:45,889
But on the morning of the third day we again raised our masts, set sail, and took our places, letting the wind and steersmen direct our ship.

31
00:03:46,004 --> 00:03:54,937
I should have got home at that time unharmed had not the north wind and the currents been against me as I was doubling Cape Malaya and set me off my course hard by the island of Cythera.

32
00:03:55,618 --> 00:04:04,732
I was driven thence by foul winds for a space of nine days upon the sea, but on the tenth day we reached the land of the lotus eaters, who live on a food that comes from a kind of flower.

33
00:04:05,272 --> 00:04:11,742
Here we landed to take in fresh water, and our crews got their midday meal on the shore near the ships.

34
00:04:11,722 --> 00:04:19,352
When they had eaten and drunk, I sent two of my company to see what manner of men the people of the place might be, and they had a third man under them.

35
00:04:20,013 --> 00:04:39,619
They started at once, and went about among the lotus-eaters, who did them no hurt, but gave them to eat of the lotus, which was so delicious that those who ate of it left off caring about home, and did not even want to go back and say what had happened to them, but were for staying and munching lotus 7-7-7 with the lotus-eaters, without thinking further of their return.

36
00:04:39,599 --> 00:04:45,184
Nevertheless, though they wept bitterly, I forced them back to the ships and made them fast under the benches.

37
00:04:45,805 --> 00:04:54,372
Then I told the rest to go on board at once, lest any of them should taste of the lotus and leave off wanting to get home, so they took their places and smote the grey sea with their oars.

38
00:04:55,073 --> 00:05:00,638
We sailed hence, always in much distress, till we came to the land of the lawless and inhuman Cyclopes.

39
00:05:01,198 --> 00:05:09,606
Now the Cyclopes neither plant nor plough, but trust in Providence, and live on such wheat, barley, and grapes as grow wild without any kind of tillage,

40
00:05:09,586 --> 00:05:13,472
and their wild grapes yield them wine as the sun and the rain may grow them.

41
00:05:14,214 --> 00:05:24,030
They have no laws nor assemblies of the people, but live in caves on the tops of high mountains, each his lord and master in his family, and they take no account of their neighbours.

42
00:05:24,050 --> 00:05:27,696
Now off their harbour there lies a wooded and fertile island,

43
00:05:27,676 --> 00:05:31,340
not quite close to the land of the Cyclopes, but still not far.

44
00:05:31,860 --> 00:05:43,573
It is overrun with wild goats, that breed there in great numbers, and are never disturbed by foot of man, for sportsmen, who as a rule will suffer so much hardship in forest or among mountain precipices.

45
00:05:44,293 --> 00:05:54,544
Do not go there, nor yet again is it ever ploughed or fed down, but it lies a wilderness untilled and unsewn from year to year, and has no living thing upon it but only goats.

46
00:05:54,727 --> 00:05:58,876
For the Cyclopes have no ships, nor yet shipwrights who could make ships for them.

47
00:05:59,257 --> 00:06:05,251
They cannot therefore go from city to city, or sail over the sea to one another's country, as people who have ships can do.

48
00:06:05,291 --> 00:06:08,318
If they had had these, they would have colonized the island.

49
00:06:08,939 --> 00:06:12,567
Seventy-eight for it is a very good one, and would yield everything in due season.

50
00:06:12,547 --> 00:06:26,167
There are meadows that in some places come right down to the seashore, well watered and full of luscious grass, grapes would do there excellently, there is level land for ploughing, and it would always yield heavily at harvest time, for the soil is deep.

51
00:06:26,788 --> 00:06:38,706
There is a good harbour where no cables are wanted, nor yet anchors, nor need a ship be moored, but all one has to do is to beach one's vessel and stay there till the wind becomes fair for putting out to sea again.

52
00:06:38,686 --> 00:06:44,574
At the head of the harbour there is a spring of clear water coming out of a cave, and there are poplars growing all round it.

53
00:06:45,115 --> 00:06:51,223
Here we entered, but so dark was the night that some god must have brought us in, for there was nothing whatever to be seen.

54
00:06:51,743 --> 00:06:53,866
A thick mist hung all round our ships.

55
00:06:54,187 --> 00:07:04,120
Seventy-nine, the moon was hidden behind a mass of clouds so that no one could have seen the island if he had looked for it, nor were there any breakers to tell us we were close inshore before we found ourselves upon the land itself,

56
00:07:04,100 --> 00:07:09,992
When, however, we had beached the ships, we took down the sails, went ashore, and camped upon the beach till daybreak.

57
00:07:10,614 --> 00:07:21,096
When the child of morning, rosy-fingered dawn, appeared, we admired the island and wandered all over it, while the nymphs Jove's daughters roused the wild goats that we might get some meat for our dinner.

58
00:07:21,076 --> 00:07:27,424
On this we fetched our spears and bows and arrows from the ships, and dividing ourselves into three bands began to shoot the goats.

59
00:07:27,924 --> 00:07:29,567
Heaven sent us excellent sport.

60
00:07:30,047 --> 00:07:34,613
I had twelve ships with me, and each ship got nine goats, while my own ship had ten.

61
00:07:35,213 --> 00:07:46,948
Thus through the livelong day to the going down of the sun we ate and drank our fill, and we had plenty of wine left, for each one of us had taken many jars full when we sacked the city of the Sykans, and this had not yet run out.

62
00:07:47,350 --> 00:07:54,403
While we were feasting we kept turning our eyes towards the land of the Cyclopes, which was hard by, and saw the smoke of their stubble fires.

63
00:07:55,265 --> 00:08:05,123
We could almost fancy we heard their voices and the bleating of their sheep and goats, but when the sun went down and it came on dark, we camped down upon the beach, and next morning I called a council.

64
00:08:05,204 --> 00:08:11,011
"'Stay here, my brave fellows,' said I, "'all the rest of you while I go with my ship "'and exploit these people myself.

65
00:08:11,532 --> 00:08:16,077
"'I want to see if they are uncivilized savages "'or a hospitable and humane race.'

66
00:08:16,097 --> 00:08:20,943
"'I went on board, bidding my men to do so also, "'and loose the horsers.

67
00:08:20,963 --> 00:08:24,307
"'So they took their places "'and smote the gray sea with their oars.

68
00:08:24,327 --> 00:08:31,836
"'When we got to the land, which was not far, "'there on the face of a cliff near the sea, "'we saw a great cave overhung with laurels.

69
00:08:31,816 --> 00:08:41,088
It was a station for a great many sheep and goats, and outside there was a large yard, with a high wall round it made of stones built into the ground and of trees both pine and oak.

70
00:08:41,108 --> 00:08:46,095
This was the abode of a huge monster who was then away from home shepherding his flocks.

71
00:08:46,876 --> 00:08:50,060
He would have nothing to do with other people, but led the life of an outlaw.

72
00:08:50,921 --> 00:08:59,612
He was a horrid creature, not like a human being at all, but resembling rather some crag that stands out boldly against the sky on the top of a high mountain.

73
00:08:59,592 --> 00:09:06,287
I told my men to draw the ship ashore and stay where they were, all but the twelve best among them, who were to go along with myself.

74
00:09:07,169 --> 00:09:17,972
I also took a goatskin of sweet black wine which had been given me by Maron, son of Euanthes, who was priest of Apollo the patron god of Ismaris, and lived within the wooded precincts of the temple.

75
00:09:17,952 --> 00:09:25,503
When we were sacking the city we respected him, and spared his life, as also his wife and child, so he made me some presents of great value.

76
00:09:26,024 --> 00:09:33,075
Seven talents of fine gold, and a bowl of silver, with twelve jars of sweet wine, unblended, and of the most exquisite flavour.

77
00:09:33,475 --> 00:09:39,184
Not a man nor maid in the house knew about it, but only himself, his wife, and one housekeeper.

78
00:09:39,164 --> 00:09:47,619
When he drank it he mixed twenty parts of water to one of wine, and yet the fragrance from the mixing bowl was so exquisite that it was impossible to refrain from drinking.

79
00:09:48,099 --> 00:10:00,160
I filled a large skin with this wine, and took a wallet full of provisions with me, for my mind misgave me that I might have to deal with some savage who would be of great strength and would respect neither right nor law.

80
00:10:00,140 --> 00:10:05,850
We soon reached his cave, but he was out shepherding, so we went inside and took stock of all that we could see.

81
00:10:05,890 --> 00:10:11,399
His cheese racks were loaded with cheeses, and he had more lambs and kids than his pens could hold.

82
00:10:12,060 --> 00:10:13,422
They were kept in separate flocks.

83
00:10:13,903 --> 00:10:20,695
First there were the hoggets, then the oldest of the younger lambs, and lastly the very young ones eighty, all kept apart from one another.

84
00:10:21,176 --> 00:10:26,164
As for his dairy, all the vessels, bowls, and milk pails into which he milked were swimming with whey.

85
00:10:26,144 --> 00:10:32,212
When they saw all this, my men begged me to let them first steal some cheeses, and make off with them to the ship.

86
00:10:32,573 --> 00:10:37,219
They would then return, drive down the lambs and kids, put them on board, and sail away with them.

87
00:10:37,699 --> 00:10:44,889
It would have been indeed better if we had done so, but I would not listen to them, for I wanted to see the owner himself, in the hope that he might give me a present.

88
00:10:45,450 --> 00:10:49,435
When, however, we saw him, my poor men found him ill to deal with.

89
00:10:49,415 --> 00:10:56,725
We lit a fire, offered some of the cheeses in sacrifice, ate others of them, and then sat waiting till the Cyclops should come in with his sheep.

90
00:10:57,246 --> 00:11:09,162
When he came, he brought in with him a huge load of dry firewood to light the fire for his supper, and this he flung with such a noise onto the floor of his cave that we hid ourselves for fear at the far end of the cavern.

91
00:11:09,665 --> 00:11:17,956
Meanwhile, he drove all the ewes inside, as well as the she-goats that he was going to milk, leaving the males, both rams and he-goats, outside in the yards.

92
00:11:18,577 --> 00:11:26,808
Then he rolled a huge stone to the mouth of the cave, so huge that two and twenty strong four-wheeled wagons would not be enough to draw it from its place against the doorway.

93
00:11:27,469 --> 00:11:33,917
When he had so done, he sat down and milked his ewes and goats, all in due course, and then let each of them have her own young.

94
00:11:34,015 --> 00:11:40,742
He curdled half the milk and set it aside in wicker strainers, but the other half he poured into bowls that he might drink it for his supper.

95
00:11:41,703 --> 00:11:47,770
When he had got through with all his work he lit the fire, and then caught sight of us, whereon he said, Strangers, who are you?

96
00:11:48,070 --> 00:11:48,931
Where do you sail from?

97
00:11:48,951 --> 00:11:50,453
Are you traders?

98
00:11:50,994 --> 00:11:56,800
Or do you sail the sea as rovers, with your hands against every man, and every man's hand against you?

99
00:11:56,780 --> 00:12:08,858
We were frightened out of our senses by his loud voice and monstrous form, but I managed to say, we are Achaeans on our way home from Troy, but by the will of Jove and stress of weather, we have been driven far out of our course.

100
00:12:09,579 --> 00:12:18,552
We are the people of Agamemnon, son of Atreus, who has won infinite renown throughout the whole world, by sacking so great a city and killing so many people.

101
00:12:18,532 --> 00:12:25,260
We therefore humbly pray you to show us some hospitality, and otherwise make us such presents as visitors may reasonably expect.

102
00:12:25,861 --> 00:12:37,275
May your excellency fear the wrath of heaven, for we are your suppliants, and Jove takes all respectable travelers under his protection, for he is the avenger of all suppliants and foreigners in distress."

103
00:12:37,876 --> 00:12:40,039
To this he gave me but a pitiless answer.

104
00:12:40,800 --> 00:12:45,265
Stranger, said he, you are a fool, or else you know nothing of this country.

105
00:12:45,245 --> 00:12:48,510
Talk to me, indeed, about fearing the gods or shunning their anger.

106
00:12:49,031 --> 00:12:54,800
We Cyclopes do not care about Jove or any of your blessed gods, for we are ever so much stronger than they.

107
00:12:54,840 --> 00:13:01,470
I shall not spare either yourself or your companions out of any regard for Jove, unless I am in the humor for doing so.

108
00:13:01,531 --> 00:13:05,176
And now tell me where you made your ship fast when you came on shore.

109
00:13:05,757 --> 00:13:09,463
Was it round the point, or is she lying straight off the land?

110
00:13:09,545 --> 00:13:14,955
He said this to draw me out, but I was too cunning to be caught in that way, so I answered with a lie.

111
00:13:15,816 --> 00:13:20,504
Neptune, said I, sent my ship onto the rocks at the far end of your country and wrecked it.

112
00:13:20,985 --> 00:13:27,216
We were driven onto them from the open sea, but I and those who were with me escaped the jaws of death.

113
00:13:27,196 --> 00:13:36,881
The cruel wretch vouchsafed me not one word of answer, but with a sudden clutch he gripped up two of my men at once and dashed them down upon the ground as though they had been puppies.

114
00:13:37,503 --> 00:13:40,972
Their brains were shed upon the ground, and the earth was wet with their blood.

115
00:13:41,373 --> 00:13:44,260
Then he tore them limb from limb and supped upon them.

116
00:13:44,240 --> 00:13:50,388
He gobbled them up like a lion in the wilderness, flesh, bones, marrow and entrails, without leaving anything uneaten.

117
00:13:51,148 --> 00:13:57,716
As for us, we wept and lifted up our hands to heaven on seeing such a horrid sight, for we did not know what else to do.

118
00:13:58,377 --> 00:14:08,830
But when the Cyclops had filled his huge paunch and had washed down his meal of human flesh with a drink of neat milk, he stretched himself full length upon the ground among his sheep and went to sleep.

119
00:14:08,810 --> 00:14:21,469
I was at first inclined to seize my sword, draw it, and drive it into his vitals, but I reflected that if I did, we should all certainly be lost, for we should never be able to shift the stone which the monster had put in front of the door.

120
00:14:22,158 --> 00:14:25,383
So we stayed sobbing and sighing where we were till morning came.

121
00:14:25,944 --> 00:14:34,217
When the child of morning, rosy-fingered Dawn, appeared, he again lit his fire, milked his goats and ewes all quite rightly, and then let each have her own young one.

122
00:14:34,838 --> 00:14:40,708
As soon as he had got through with all his work, he clutched up two more of my men and began eating them for his morning's meal.

123
00:14:41,349 --> 00:14:47,018
Presently, with the utmost ease, he rolled the stone away from the door and drove out his sheep.

124
00:14:46,998 --> 00:14:52,948
But he at once put it back again, as easily as though he were merely clapping the lid onto a quiver full of arrows.

125
00:14:53,569 --> 00:14:59,318
As soon as he had done so, he shouted and cried, shoo, shoo, after his sheep to drive them onto the mountain.

126
00:14:59,819 --> 00:15:04,367
So I was left to scheme some way of taking my revenge and covering myself with glory.

127
00:15:05,148 --> 00:15:08,133
In the end, I deemed it would be the best plan to do as follows.

128
00:15:08,754 --> 00:15:12,039
The Cyclops had a great club which was lying near one of the sheep pens.

129
00:15:12,520 --> 00:15:13,782
It was of green olivewood.

130
00:15:13,762 --> 00:15:17,767
and he had cut it intending to use it for a staff as soon as it should be dry.

131
00:15:18,467 --> 00:15:26,377
It was so huge that we could only compare it to the mast of a twenty-odd merchant vessel of large burden, and able to venture out into open sea.

132
00:15:27,037 --> 00:15:29,520
I went up to this club and cut off about six feet of it.

133
00:15:30,061 --> 00:15:40,393
I then gave this piece to the men and told them to fine it evenly off at one end, which they proceeded to do, and lastly I brought it to a point myself, charring the end in the fire to make it harder.

134
00:15:40,373 --> 00:15:51,456
When I had done this, I hid it under dung, which was lying about all over the cave, and told the men to cast lots which of them should venture along with myself to lift it and bore it into the monster's eye while he was asleep.

135
00:15:52,097 --> 00:15:56,847
The lot fell upon the very four whom I should have chosen, and I myself made five.

136
00:15:56,827 --> 00:16:04,919
In the evening, the wretch came back from shepherding and drove his flocks into the cave, this time driving them all inside, and not leaving any in the yards.

137
00:16:05,480 --> 00:16:09,627
I suppose some fancy must have taken him, or a god must have prompted him to do so.

138
00:16:10,148 --> 00:16:18,320
As soon as he had put the stone back to its place against the door, he sat down, milked his ewes and his goats all quite rightly, and then let each have her own young one.

139
00:16:18,861 --> 00:16:24,049
When he had got through with all this work, he gripped up two more of my men and made his supper off them.

140
00:16:24,029 --> 00:16:27,555
So I went up to him with an ivy-wood bowl of black wine in my hands.

141
00:16:28,236 --> 00:16:36,389
Look here, Cyclops, said I, you have been eating a great deal of man's flesh, so take this and drink some wine, that you may see what kind of liquor we had on board my ship.

142
00:16:37,210 --> 00:16:43,540
I was bringing it to you as a drink offering, in the hope that you would take compassion upon me and further me on my way home,

143
00:16:43,520 --> 00:16:47,126
whereas all you do is to go on ramping and raving most intolerably.

144
00:16:47,166 --> 00:16:49,070
You ought to be ashamed of yourself.

145
00:16:49,430 --> 00:16:52,877
How can you expect people to come see you anymore if you treat them in this way?"

146
00:16:53,598 --> 00:16:55,060
He then took the cup and drank.

147
00:16:55,722 --> 00:16:59,629
He was so delighted with the taste of the wine that he begged me for another bowl full.

148
00:17:00,490 --> 00:17:04,397
Be so kind, he said, as to give me some more and tell me your name at once.

149
00:17:04,998 --> 00:17:07,823
I want to make you a present that you will be glad to have.

150
00:17:07,904 --> 00:17:15,658
We have wine even in this country, for our soil grows grapes and the sun ripens them, but this drinks like nectar and ambrosia all in one.

151
00:17:16,620 --> 00:17:23,432
I then gave him some more, three times did I fill the bowl for him, and three times did he drain it without thought or heed.

152
00:17:23,412 --> 00:17:31,246
Then, when I saw that the wine had got into his head, I said to him as plausibly as I could, Cyclops, you ask my name and I will tell it you.

153
00:17:31,687 --> 00:17:33,670
Give me, therefore, the present you promised me.

154
00:17:33,991 --> 00:17:34,812
My name is Noman.

155
00:17:35,253 --> 00:17:38,198
This is what my father and mother and my friends have always called me.

156
00:17:39,089 --> 00:17:45,501
But the cruel wretch said, Then I will eat all Noman's comrades before Noman himself, and will keep Noman for the last.

157
00:17:45,922 --> 00:17:47,465
This is the present that I will make him.

158
00:17:48,166 --> 00:17:51,913
As he spoke he reeled and fell sprawling face upwards on the ground.

159
00:17:52,414 --> 00:17:56,862
His great neck hung heavily backwards, and a deep sleep took hold upon him.

160
00:17:56,842 --> 00:18:03,312
Presently he turned sick and threw up both wine and the gobbets of human flesh on which he had been gorging, for he was very drunk.

161
00:18:03,953 --> 00:18:10,083
Then I thrust the beam of wood far into the embers to heat it, and encouraged my men lest any of them should turn faint-hearted.

162
00:18:10,584 --> 00:18:19,137
When the wood, green though it was, was about to blaze, I drew it out of the fire glowing with heat, and my men gathered round me, for heaven had filled their hearts with courage.

163
00:18:19,454 --> 00:18:33,291
We drove the sharp end of the beam into the monster's eye, and bearing upon it with all my weight, I kept turning it round and round, as though I were boring a hole in a ship's plank with an auger, which two men with a wheel and strap can keep on turning as long as they choose.

164
00:18:34,132 --> 00:18:40,720
Even thus did we bore the red-hot beam into his eye, till the boiling blood bubbled all over it as we worked it round and round,

165
00:18:40,700 --> 00:18:51,418
so that the steam from the burning eyeball scalded his eyelids and eyebrows, and the roots of the eye sputtered in the fire, as a blacksmith plunges an axe or hatchet into cold water to temper it.

166
00:18:51,919 --> 00:18:55,966
For it is this that gives strength to the iron, and it makes a great hiss as he does so.

167
00:18:56,326 --> 00:19:02,657
Even thus did the cyclops's eye hiss round the beam of olivewood, and his hideous yells made the cave ring again.

168
00:19:02,637 --> 00:19:13,832
We ran away in a fright, but he plucked the beam all besmirched with gore from his eye, and hurled it from him in a frenzy of rage and pain, shouting as he did so to the other Cyclopes who lived on the bleak headlands near him.

169
00:19:14,253 --> 00:19:18,759
So they gathered from all quarters round his cave when they heard him crying, and asked what was the matter with him.

170
00:19:19,340 --> 00:19:26,650
What ails you, Polyphemus, said they, that you make such a noise, breaking the stillness of the night, and preventing us from being able to sleep?

171
00:19:27,231 --> 00:19:29,674
Surely no man is carrying off your sheep.

172
00:19:29,654 --> 00:19:33,825
Surely no man is trying to kill you either by fraud or by force.

173
00:19:33,957 --> 00:19:40,186
But Polyphemus shouted to them from inside the cave, No man is killing me by fraud, no man is killing me by force.

174
00:19:41,007 --> 00:19:44,453
Then, said they, if no man is attacking you, you must be ill.

175
00:19:44,793 --> 00:19:49,220
When Jove makes people ill, there is no help for it, and you had better pray to your father Neptune.

176
00:19:49,260 --> 00:19:53,907
Then they went away, and I laughed inwardly at the success of my clever stratagem.

177
00:19:54,407 --> 00:20:00,977
But the Cyclops, groaning and in an agony of pain, felt about with his hands till he found the stone and took it from the door.

178
00:20:00,957 --> 00:20:08,032
Then he sat in the doorway and stretched his hands in front of it to catch anyone going out with the sheep, for he thought I might be foolish enough to attempt this.

179
00:20:08,733 --> 00:20:13,663
As for myself, I kept on puzzling to think how I could best save my own life and those of my companions.

180
00:20:14,144 --> 00:20:19,776
I schemed and schemed, as one who knows that his life depends upon it, for the danger was very great.

181
00:20:19,756 --> 00:20:22,463
In the end, I deemed that this plan would be the best.

182
00:20:22,984 --> 00:20:32,348
The male sheep were well grown, and carried a heavy black fleece, so I bound them noiselessly in threes together with some of the withies on which the wicked monster used to sleep.

183
00:20:32,935 --> 00:20:39,026
There was to be a man under the middle sheep, and the two on either side were to cover him, so that there were three sheep to each man.

184
00:20:39,687 --> 00:20:52,149
As for myself, there was a ram finer than any of the others, so I caught hold of him by the back, esconced myself in the thick wool under his belly, and hung on patiently to his fleece, face upwards, keeping a firm hold on it all the time.

185
00:20:52,730 --> 00:20:56,597
Thus then did we wait in great fear of mind till morning came.

186
00:20:56,577 --> 00:21:07,632
But when the child of morning, rosy-fingered Dawn, appeared, the male sheep hurried out to feed, while the ewes remained bleating about the pens waiting to be milked, for their udders were full to bursting.

187
00:21:08,093 --> 00:21:16,324
But their master, in spite of all his pain, felt the backs of all the sheep as they stood upright, without being sharp enough to find out that the men were underneath their bellies.

188
00:21:16,304 --> 00:21:28,685
As the ram was going out, last of all, heavy with its fleece and with the weight of my crafty self, Polyphemus laid hold of it and said, My good ram, what is it that makes you the last to leave my cave this morning?

189
00:21:29,446 --> 00:21:40,405
You are not wont to let the ewes go before you, but lead the mob with a run, whether to flowery mead or bubbling fountain, and are the first to come home again at night, but now you lag last of all.

190
00:21:40,537 --> 00:21:48,269
Is it because you know your master has lost his eye, and are sorry because that wicked gnomon and his horrid crew has got him down in his drink and blinded him?

191
00:21:48,889 --> 00:21:50,131
But I will have his life yet.

192
00:21:50,632 --> 00:21:58,263
If you could understand and talk, you would tell me where the wretch is hiding, and I would dash his brains upon the ground till they flew all over the cave.

193
00:21:58,804 --> 00:22:02,730
I should thus have some satisfaction for the harm this no-good gnomon has done me.

194
00:22:03,233 --> 00:22:11,628
As he spoke he drove the ram outside, but when we were a little way out from the cave and yards, I first got from under the ram's belly and then freed my comrades.

195
00:22:12,149 --> 00:22:18,200
As for the sheep, which were very fat, by constantly heading them in the right direction, we managed to drive them down to the ship.

196
00:22:18,862 --> 00:22:25,073
The crew rejoiced greatly at seeing those of us who had escaped death, but wept for the others whom the Cyclops had killed.

197
00:22:25,053 --> 00:22:32,405
However, I made signs to them by nodding and frowning that they were to hush their crying, and told them to get all the sheep on board at once and put out to sea.

198
00:22:32,826 --> 00:22:36,552
So they went aboard, took their places, and smote the grey sea with their oars.

199
00:22:37,313 --> 00:22:41,920
Then, when I had got as far out as my voice would reach, I began to jeer at the Cyclops.

200
00:22:42,622 --> 00:22:48,211
Cyclops, said I, you should have taken better measure of your man before eating up his comrades in your cave.

201
00:22:48,551 --> 00:22:51,516
You wretch, eat up your visitors in your own house.

202
00:22:51,496 --> 00:22:56,428
you might have known that your sin would find you out, and now Jove and the other gods have punished you."

203
00:22:57,411 --> 00:23:07,395
He got more and more furious as he heard me, so he tore the top from off a high mountain and flung it just in front of my ship so that it was within a little of hitting the end of the rudder 281.

204
00:23:07,375 --> 00:23:15,072
The sea quaked as the rock fell into it, and the wash of the wave it raised carried us back towards the mainland and forced us towards the shore.

205
00:23:15,593 --> 00:23:24,473
But I snatched up a long pole and kept the ship off, making signs to my men by nodding my head that they must row for their lives, whereon they laid out with a will.

206
00:23:24,453 --> 00:23:31,404
When we had got twice as far as we were before, I was for jeering at the Cyclops again, but the men begged and prayed of me to hold my tongue.

207
00:23:31,765 --> 00:23:36,252
Do not, they exclaimed, be mad enough to provoke this savage creature further.

208
00:23:36,713 --> 00:23:42,562
He has thrown one rock at us already, which drove us back again to the mainland, and we made sure it had been the death of us.

209
00:23:43,263 --> 00:23:52,097
If he had then heard any further sound of voices, he would have pounded our heads and our ship's timbers into a jelly with the rugged rocks he would have heaved at us, for he can throw them a long way.

210
00:23:53,343 --> 00:24:05,340
But I would not listen to them, and shouted out to him in my rage, Cyclops, if anyone asks you who it was that put your eye out and spoiled your beauty, say it was the valiant warrior Ulysses, son of LaÃ«rtes, who lives in Ithaca.

211
00:24:06,522 --> 00:24:11,530
On this he groaned and cried out, Alas, alas, alas, than the old prophecy about.

212
00:24:11,750 --> 00:24:13,933
There was a prophet here, at one time.

213
00:24:13,913 --> 00:24:22,425
a man both brave and of great stature, Telemus son of Eurymus, who was an excellent seer, and did all the prophesying for the Cyclopes till he grew old.

214
00:24:23,006 --> 00:24:27,792
He told me that all this would happen to me someday, and said I should lose my sight by the hand of Ulysses.

215
00:24:28,593 --> 00:24:40,009
I have been all along expecting someone of imposing presence and superhuman strength, whereas he turns out to be a little insignificant weakling, who has managed to blind my eye by taking advantage of me and my drink.

216
00:24:40,390 --> 00:24:41,912
Come here then, Ulysses,

217
00:24:41,892 --> 00:24:47,340
that I may make you presents to show my hospitality and urge Neptune to help you forward on your journey.

218
00:24:48,001 --> 00:24:49,944
For Neptune and I are father and son.

219
00:24:50,004 --> 00:24:55,272
He, if he so will, shall heal me, which no one else, neither God nor man, can do."

220
00:24:55,312 --> 00:25:05,487
Then I said, I wish I could be as sure of killing you outright and sending you down to the house of Hades as I am that it will take more than Neptune to cure that eye of yours.

221
00:25:05,467 --> 00:25:26,833
On this he lifted up his hands to the firmament of heaven and prayed, saying, Hear me, great Neptune, if I am indeed your own true begotten son, grant that Ulysses may never reach his home alive, or if he must get back to his friends at last, let him do so late and in sore plight after losing all his men let him reach his home in another man's ship and find trouble in his house.

222
00:25:26,813 --> 00:25:30,460
Eighty-two, thus did he pray, and Neptune heard his prayer.

223
00:25:30,480 --> 00:25:35,270
Then he picked up a rock much larger than the first, swung it aloft, and hurled it with prodigious force.

224
00:25:36,131 --> 00:25:39,839
It fell just short of the ship, but was within a little of hitting the end of the rudder.

225
00:25:40,580 --> 00:25:46,712
The sea quaked as the rock fell into it, and the wash of the wave it raised drove us onwards on our way towards the shore of the island.

226
00:25:47,182 --> 00:25:54,719
When at last we got to the island where we had left the rest of our ships, we found our comrades lamenting us and anxiously awaiting our return.

227
00:25:55,420 --> 00:25:58,908
We ran our vessel upon the sands and got out of her onto the seashore.

228
00:25:59,569 --> 00:26:06,304
We also landed the Cyclops' sheep and divided them equitably amongst us so that none might have reason to complain.

229
00:26:06,284 --> 00:26:15,575
As for the ram, my companions agreed that I should have it as an extra share, so I sacrificed it on the seashore, and burned its thigh bones to Jove, who is the Lord of all.

230
00:26:16,156 --> 00:26:21,302
But he heeded not my sacrifice, and only thought how he might destroy both my ships and my comrades.

231
00:26:21,923 --> 00:26:32,055
Thus through the lifelong day to the going down of the sun, we feasted our fill on meat and drink, but when the sun went down and it came on dark, we camped upon the beach.

232
00:26:32,035 --> 00:26:37,089
When the child of morning rosy-fingered dawn appeared, I bade my men on board and loose the horses.

233
00:26:37,551 --> 00:26:40,519
Then they took their places and smote the grey sea with their oars.

234
00:26:40,981 --> 00:26:46,737
So we sailed on with sorrow in our hearts, but glad to have escaped death, though we had lost our comrades.

